'''Andrew Brackman''' (born [[December 4]], [[1985]]) is a 6' 10" [[right-handed]] [[Major League Baseball]] [[pitcher]] with the [[New York Yankees]] organization.<ref>[http://www.minorleaguebaseball.com/milb/events/draft_report/y2007/index.jsp?mc=brackman Draft Report for Andrew Brackman]</ref> He signed a four year $4.55 million dollar deal with $3.35 million signing bonus as the 30th overall pick of the [[2007 Major League Baseball Draft | 2007 Major League Baseball draft]].<ref name=CSTV.com>{{cite news
| url=http://www.cstv.com/sports/m-basebl/stories/081607aaa.html
| title=Yankees Agree to Deal With First-Rounder Andrew Brackman
| publisher=[[CBS College Sports Network|CSTV.com]]
| date=[[2007-08-15]]
| accessdate=2008-02-27
}}</ref>  Brackman is represented by sports agent [[Scott Boras]].<ref name=RotoWorld.com>
{{cite news
| url=http://www.rotoworld.com/content/playerpages/player_main.aspx?sport=MLB&id=4564
| title=Andrew Brackman - Starting Pitcher
| publisher=[[Rotoworld.com]]
| date=[[2007-08-27]]
| accessdate=2008-02-27
}}</ref>


==High school career==

Brackman attended [[Moeller High School]] in [[Cincinnati, OH]].  There he was one of the top high school pitchers in the country, and a two-sport standout.  He had a career ERA of 1.04, the seventh best in the history of Ohio high school baseball,<ref name=MLB.com>
{{cite news
| url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080221&content_id=2382413&vkey=spt2008news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb
| title=Minor League Report: Young pitchers
| publisher=[[MLB.com]]
| date=[[2008-02-21]]
| accessdate=2008-02-27
}}</ref> and helped lead Moeller to a 28-3 record and the Ohio state championship as a senior.  He was ranked as the No. 18 senior in America by [[Team One Baseball]], and listed as the No. 4 prospect in Ohio for the 2004 draft by [[Baseball America]]. 

He was runner-up for Mr. Basketball in Ohio by the [[Associated Press]], shared Ohio's Division I Player of the Year honors, and was named first-team all-state, as he averaged 20.2 points and 6.5 rebounds as a senior.  He led his conference in scoring and field-goal percentage (.654), and was second in free-throw percentage (.882).  He was rated the No. 42 prospect nationally by Insiders.com, and No. 43 by PrepStars following his senior season.<ref name=GoPack.com>
{{cite news
| url=http://www.gopack.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=9200&ATCLID=606227
| title=Wolfpack Biographies - Andrew Brackman
| publisher=[[Gopack.com]]
| date=[[2006-09-13]]
| accessdate=2008-02-27
}}</ref>

== College career ==
He then attended and played at [[North Carolina State University]].  Brackman played two seasons as a dual-sport athlete at NC State, playing both basketball and baseball. During his freshman year basketball season (2004-2005), he played center and forward averaging 7.4 points and 3.5 rebounds.<ref name=CBS>
{{cite news
| url=http://cbs.sportsline.com/collegebasketball/story/8491812
| title=Brackman's talent will stay on display at N.C. State
| publisher=[[CBS.Sportsline.com]]
| date=[[2005-05-23]]
| accessdate=2008-02-27
}}</ref>

In his freshman baseball season, he was 4-0 with a 2.09 ERA in 10 appearances as both a reliever and later, a starting pitcher.  He was starting pitcher of the first game of the [[2005 ACC Baseball Tournament]], striking out five batters in seven innings to earn the victory against the [[Miami Hurricanes baseball | Miami Hurricanes]].  He was named a second-team preseason All-America player by [[Baseball America]] for [[2006]].  <ref name=GoPack.com>
{{cite news
| url=http://www.gopack.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=9200&ATCLID=606227
| title=Wolfpack Biographies - Andrew Brackman
| publisher=[[Gopack.com]]
| date=[[2006-09-13]]
| accessdate=2008-02-27
}}</ref>
After the [[NC State Wolfpack| Wolfpack]] was knocked out of the [[2006 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament| 2006 NCAA tournament]], in the second round by Texas, Brackman chose not to return to the basketball team the next season and instead to develop his pitching with hopes of doing well in professional baseball.  

Brackman suffered a  stress fracture to his hip in his sophomore year basketball season limiting him to only 7 games and a disappointing 1-4 record with a 6.09 ERA.<ref name=ESPN>
{{cite news
| url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/columns/story?columnist=katz_andy&id=2614344
| title=Brackman, busy with baseball, hasn't decided on return
| publisher=[[ESPN]]
| date=[[2006-10-05]]
| accessdate=2008-02-27
}}</ref><ref>[http://www.thebaseballcube.com/players/B/Andrew-Brackman.shtml Andrew Brackman Statistics - The Baseball Cube<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  In the summer of that year, he pitched for the [[Orleans Cardinals]] in the [[Cape Cod League]] earning a 1-0 record with a 1.09 ERA.<ref name=ESPN>
{{cite news
| url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/columns/story?columnist=katz_andy&id=2614344
| title=Brackman, busy with baseball, hasn't decided on return
| publisher=[[ESPN]]
| date=[[2006-10-05]]
| accessdate=2008-02-27
}}</ref> This effort led to [[Baseball America]] ranking him the number 2 prospect in that league.  

Brackman's junior year at NC State saw a return to his freshman year numbers: in 13 games, he struck out 74 batters in 78 innings with a 3.81 ERA and a record of 6-4.  He did not pitch in the ACC nor the NCAA tournaments due to elbow injuries.<ref name=NewYorkPost>
{{cite news
| url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/08272007/sports/yankees/yanks__top_pick_to_have_surger.htm
| title=Yanks's top pick to have surgery
| publisher=[[New York Post]]
| date=[[2007-08-27]]
| accessdate=2008-02-27
}}</ref>

Despite anxiety about the effect of his past injuries on his draft stock, Brackman did well in the [[2007 Major League Baseball Draft]], drafted by the Yankees with the 30th pick of the first round<ref>[http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/events/draft/y2007/drafttracker.jsp 2007 MLB.com Draft tracker]</ref>.

==Professional career==
Following the 2007 draft, the Yankees signed Brackman to a guaranteed $4.5 million deal for four years including a $3.55 million signing bonus spread out over six years.<ref name=NewYorkTimes>
{{cite news
| url=http://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/17/sports/baseball/17pins.html?_r=1&fta=y&oref=slogin
| title=Good News on the Health of the Yankees<U+2019> Top Pick
| publisher=[[New York Times]]
| author=[[Tyler Kepner]]
| date=[[2007-08-17]]
| accessdate=2008-02-27
}}</ref>  The club also holds options over Brackman for the 2011, 2012, and 2013 seasons which could boost the total value of his contract over $13 million (if he meets his bonus requirements).<ref name=NewYorkTimes>
{{cite news
| url=http://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/17/sports/baseball/17pins.html?_r=1&fta=y&oref=slogin
| title=Good News on the Health of the Yankees<U+2019> Top Pick
| publisher=[[New York Times]]
| author=[[Tyler Kepner]]
| date=[[2007-08-17]]
| accessdate=2008-02-27
}}</ref>

After he signed the contract on August 15, 2007, the Yankees placed Brackman on the 40 man roster (designating [[infielder]] [[Chris Basak]] for assignment to make room for him).<ref name=CSTV.com>{{cite news
| url=http://www.cstv.com/sports/m-basebl/stories/081607aaa.html
| title=Yankees Agree to Deal With First-Rounder Andrew Brackman
| publisher=[[CSTV.com]]
| date=[[2007-08-15]]
| accessdate=2008-02-27
}}</ref>  Brackman wears uniform number 64.

Brackman was optioned to the [[Tampa Yankees | Class-A Tampa Yankees]] in the [[Gulf Coast League]].  The Yankees recommended that Brackman see [[James Andrews (physician) | Dr. James Andrews]] in Alabama to address his lingering elbow concerns.  Later in August 2007, he underwent [[Tommy John surgery]].<ref name=NewYorkPost>
{{cite news
| url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/08272007/sports/yankees/yanks__top_pick_to_have_surger.htm
| title=Yanks's top pick to have surgery
| publisher=[[New York Post]]
| author=George King
| date=[[2007-08-27]]
| accessdate=2008-02-27
}}</ref>

Brackman is currently at the Yankee spring training camp and is slated to begin the 2008 season on the 60 day disabled list.  Despite this setback, Brackman is still considered a "blue-chip prospect".<ref name=NewYorkDailyNews>{{cite news
| url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/yankees/2008/02/26/2008-02-26_hank_steinbrenner_ill_look_at_big_pictur.html
| title=Hank Steinbrenner: I'll look at big picture for Cashman contract talks
| publisher=[[New York Daily News]]
| author=[[Mark Feinsand]]
| date=[[2008-02-26]]
| accessdate=2008-02-27
}}</ref> On February 1, 2008, [[Keith Law]] of [[ESPN]] ranked Brackman in the top 100 baseball prospects of 2008,<ref>[http://insider.espn.go.com/mlb/insider/columns/story?columnist=law_keith&id=3221365&action=login&appRedirect=http%3a%2f%2finsider.espn.go.com%2fmlb%2finsider%2fcolumns%2fstory%3fcolumnist%3dlaw_keith%26id%3d3221365 ESPN - Top 100 prospects of 2008 - MLB<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://riveraveblues.com/2008/01/31/keith-laws-top-100-prospects-2073/ River Ave. Blues | Keith Law<U+2019>s Top 100 Prospects<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>   and both Baseball America and [[Baseball Prospectus]] list him as in the Yankees' top ten prospects.<ref>[http://www.baseballamerica.com/today/prospects/features/265405.html BaseballAmerica.com: Prospects: Top 10 Prospects: New York Yankees<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://baseballprospectus.com/article.php?articleid=6957 Baseball Prospectus | Articles | Future Shock: Yankees Top 11 Prospects<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  On February 25, 2008, [[Hank Steinbrenner]] said: {{quotation|"I'm very confident in the next 10 years that [[Joba Chamberlain | Chamberlain]], [[Phil Hughes | Hughes]], [[Ian Kennedy  | Kennedy]], (Andrew) Brackman, [[Alan Horne | (Alan) Horne]] - all those guys - we're going to be a powerhouse for the next 10 years and longer."<ref name=NewYorkDailyNews2>{{cite news
| url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/yankees/2008/02/26/2008-02-26_kids_on_hank_steinbrenners_radar.html
